function xorBeauty(nums) {
    const n = nums.length;
    const maxXOR = 1024;
    const counter = new Array(maxXOR).fill(0);

    for (const num of nums) {
        counter[num % maxXOR]++;
    }

    let xor_beauty = 0;
    for (let i = 0; i < maxXOR; i++) {
        for (let j = i; j < maxXOR; j++) {
            const k = (i | j) & (~(i ^ j));
            if (k < maxXOR && k >= j) {
                let count = counter[i] * counter[j] * (i === j ? 1 : 2);
                if (k !== i && k !== j) {
                    count *= counter[k];
                }
                xor_beauty ^= count;
            }
        }
    }

    return xor_beauty;
}
```


    For each possible index triple (`i`, `j`, `k`), we compute the effective value `(nums[i] | nums[j]) & nums[k]`. Instead of iterating over the indices, we iterate over the actual values, which are limited by the maximum value for bitwise operations (1024).

First, we calculate the count for each value in `nums` modulo `maxXOR` and store it in an array `counter`. Then, we iterate over all pairs of distinct values `i` and `j`, and we determine `k = (i | j) & (~(i ^ j))`. If `k` is within the boundaries of our `counter` array and greater or equal to `j`, we compute the count of this triplet and XOR it with our current `xor_beauty` value.

Finally, we return the computed `xor_beauty` value.

